messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

1) Endpoint

4) Endpoint

- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

5) Endpoint
- Path: /api/users/{id}
- allMethods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The router in routes/userRoutes.js is mounted at the prefix /api/users in server.js (app.use('/api/users', userRoutes)), so each route in the router is prefixed with /api/users.
- The router defines these paths:
  - '/' -> router.route('/').post(...).get(...)  => POST and GET on /api/users
  - '/auth' -> router.post('/auth', ...) => POST on /api/users/auth
  - '/logout' -> router.post('/logout', ...) => POST on /api/users/logout
  - '/profile' -> .get(...).put(...) => GET and PUT on /api/users/profile
  - '/:id' -> .delete(...).get(...).put(...) => DELETE, GET, PUT on /api/users/{id} (':id' converted to {id})
- I set "allMethods" to false for all endpoints because the code does not use a router.all(...) or an equivalent that would accept every HTTP method.
- I set HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE to false for all endpoints because there are no explicit router.head(...), router.options(...), or router.trace(...) handlers in the code you provided. The determination follows the code only, per your instruction rather than implicit framework behavior.
- Each listed method marked true is present explicitly in routes/userRoutes.js for that route.
